                    <heading>Defence</heading>
                    <p id="EE.DIR.526">As assessed at November 2023, Estonia's total armed forces numbered 7,100, including an army of 3,750 (including conscripts), a navy of 450, and an air force of 400. There were also reserves of 41,200. The duration of military service is eight months, or 11 months for officers and some specialists. Estonia became a member of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in 2004. In 2007 the Baltic states (Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania) agreed to establish a joint Baltic battalion to participate in the NATO Response Force from 2010. After Russia’s annexation of Crimea from Ukraine in 2014, NATO member states deployed fighter aircraft to Estonia, based at the new Ämari airbase, as part of its Baltic air-policing mission. NATO command centres (each with some 40 officers) were set up in Estonia in 2015, as part of efforts to create an expanded rapid reaction force. The Government welcomed the decision adopted by NATO in July 2016 to deploy four multinational battalions to the Baltic states and Poland. In January 2017 Estonia signed a Defence Co-operation Agreement with the USA. In December 2021 the Government approved a new National Defence Development Plan to 2031, which was to develop Estonia’s defence capacity, reflecting concerns relating to the deteriorating security environment and Russian military activity. The Government plans to increase defence spending from 2.5% of gross domestic product to 3.0% during 2024-27. At November 2023 the NATO battlegroup in Estonia had a total strength of around 1,350 personnel, principally from the United Kingdom and France.</p>
